{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/sinusitis/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"2e4afda1-e9d5-5296-a027-01f4617ab6d0","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 94ec2dbc-ab83-4812-89af-9c135500f469 --><h1>Sinusitis: Summary</h1><!-- end field 94ec2dbc-ab83-4812-89af-9c135500f469 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 359b344f-9ad5-4c91-bbbe-97083e97f819 --><!-- begin field 286fbd96-fbd8-439e-b117-be3d230db174 --><ul><li>Sinusitis is defined as symptomatic inflammation of the paranasal sinuses.</li><li>Acute sinusitis is usually triggered by a viral upper respiratory tract infection and is defined by symptoms that last for <em>less </em>than 12 weeks.<ul><li>In adults, it is diagnosed by the presence of nasal blockage <em>or </em>nasal discharge <em>with </em>facial pain/pressure (or headache) and/or reduction of the sense of smell.</li><li>In children, it is diagnosed by the presence of nasal blockage <em>or </em>discoloured nasal discharge <em>with </em>facial pain/pressure and/or cough.</li><li>Examination may reveal the presence of purulent discharge, mucosal oedema, tenderness over the sinuses, and fever.</li><li>Acute bacterial sinusitis is suspected when symptoms last longer than 10 days and include discoloured or purulent nasal discharge, severe local pain, fever greater than 38ºC, and deterioration after an initial mild illness.</li></ul></li><li>Chronic sinusitis is defined by symptoms which last for <em>longer </em>than 12 weeks with objective evidence of sinonasal inflammation on examination.<ul><li>In adults, it is diagnosed by the presence of nasal blockage <em>or </em>nasal discharge <em>with </em>facial pain or pressure (or headache) and/or reduction of the sense of smell.</li><li>In children, it is diagnosed by the presence of nasal blockage <em>or </em>nasal discharge <em>with </em>facial pain (or pressure) and/or cough.</li><li>On examination, signs which support a diagnosis of chronic sinusitis include nasal inflammation, mucosal oedema, and mucopurulent nasal discharge.</li></ul></li><li>If signs and symptoms are not typical of sinusitis and the diagnosis is in doubt, referral to an ear, nose and throat specialist should be arranged to rule out an alternative diagnosis. Urgent referral for further investigation is required:<ul><li>For acute sinusitis — if symptoms suggest neoplasm (for example, unilateral polyp or mass, bloody nasal discharge).</li><li>For chronic sinusitis — if there are unilateral symptoms, epistaxis, blood-stained discharge, crusting, orbital symptoms (such as diplopia or reduced visual acuity), or neurological symptoms or signs.</li></ul></li><li>Management of acute sinusitis includes:<ul><li>Advice about the natural course and cause of the infection.</li><li>Recommending measures to relieve symptoms, such as analgesia for pain or fever.</li><li>Considering the need for antibiotics.</li><li>Considering high-dose intranasal corticosteroids in adults with more severe or prolonged symptoms.</li></ul></li><li>Management of chronic sinusitis includes:<ul><li>Managing any associated disorder, such as allergic rhinitis or asthma.</li><li>Advice on avoiding exacerbating factors such as allergic triggers.</li><li>Recommending measures to relieve symptoms, such as nasal irrigation with saline solution.</li><li>Considering the need for intranasal corticosteroids (especially if there is suspicion of an allergic cause).</li><li>Considering the need for long-term antibiotics (and starting treatment only after discussing this with a specialist).</li></ul></li><li>Urgent hospital admission should be arranged if there is severe systemic infection, or if a complication of acute sinusitis develops, such as orbital or intracranial involvement.<ul></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 286fbd96-fbd8-439e-b117-be3d230db174 --><!-- end item 359b344f-9ad5-4c91-bbbe-97083e97f819 -->","topic":{"id":"6d2333af-